# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: caching
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:caching/cache-coherence] In computer architecture, **cache coherence** is the uniformity of shared resource data that is stored in multiple local caches.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] In a cache coherent system, if multiple clients have a cached copy of the same region of a shared memory resource, all copies are the same.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] Without cache coherence, a change made to the region by one client may not be seen by others, and errors can result when the data used by different clients is mismatched.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] A cache coherence protocol is used to maintain cache coherency.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] The two main types are snooping and directory-based protocols.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] Cache coherence is of particular relevance in multiprocessing systems, where each CPU may have its own local cache of a shared memory resource.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] In a shared memory multiprocessor system with a separate cache memory for each processor, it is possible to have many copies of shared data: one copy in the main memory and one in the local cache of each processor that requested it.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] When one of the copies of data is changed, the other copies must reflect that change.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] Cache coherence is the discipline which ensures that the changes in the values of shared operands (data) are propagated throughout the system in a timely fashion.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] Changes to the data in any cache must be propagated to other copies (of that cache line) in the peer caches.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] Reads/Writes to a single memory location must be seen by all processors in the same order.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] Theoretically, coherence can be performed at the load/store granularity.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] However, in practice it is generally performed at the granularity of cache blocks.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] Coherence defines the behavior of reads and writes to a single address location.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] In a multiprocessor system, consider that more than one processor has cached a copy of the memory location X.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] In a read made by a processor P1 to location X that follows a write by another processor P2 to X, with no other writes to X made by any processor occurring between the two accesses and with the read and write being sufficiently separated, X must always return the value written by P2.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] This condition defines the concept of coherent view of memory.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] Propagating the writes to the shared memory location ensures that all the caches have a coherent view of the memory.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] If processor P1 reads the old value of X, even after the write by P2, we say that the memory is incoherent.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] The above conditions satisfy the **Write Propagation criteria** required for cache coherence.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] However, they are not sufficient as they do not satisfy the **Transaction Serialization condition**.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] A multi-processor system consists of four processors - P1, P2, P3 and P4, all containing cached copies of a shared variable *S* whose initial value is 0.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] Processor P1 changes the value of *S* (in its cached copy) to 10 following which processor P2 changes the value of *S* in its own cached copy to 20.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] If we ensure only write propagation, then P3 and P4 will certainly see the changes made to *S* by P1 and P2.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] However, P3 may see the change made by P1 after seeing the change made by P2 and hence return 10 on a read to *S*.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] P4 on the other hand may see changes made by P1 and P2 in the order in which they are made and hence return 20 on a read to *S*.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] The processors P3 and P4 now have an incoherent view of the memory.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] The alternative definition of a coherent system is via the definition of sequential consistency memory model: "the cache coherent system must appear to execute all threads’ loads and stores to a *single* memory location in a total order that respects the program order of each thread".
[src:caching/cache-coherence] Thus, the only difference between the cache coherent system and sequentially consistent system is in the number of address locations the definition talks about (single memory location for a cache coherent system, and all memory locations for a sequentially consistent system).
[src:caching/cache-coherence] Another definition is: "a multiprocessor is cache consistent if all writes to the same memory location are performed in some sequential order".
[src:caching/cache-coherence] Rarely, but especially in algorithms, coherence can instead refer to the locality of reference.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] Multiple copies of the same data can exist in different cache simultaneously and if processors are allowed to update their own copies freely, an inconsistent view of memory can result.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] The two most common mechanisms of ensuring coherency are *snooping* and *directory-based*, each having their own benefits and drawbacks.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] Snooping based protocols tend to be faster, if enough bandwidth is available, since all transactions are a request/response seen by all processors.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] The drawback is that snooping isn't scalable.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] Every request must be broadcast to all nodes in a system, meaning that as the system gets larger, the size of the (logical or physical) bus and the bandwidth it provides must grow.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] Directories, on the other hand, tend to have longer latency (with a 3 hop request-forward-respond) but use much less bandwidth since messages are point to point and not broadcast.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] For this reason, many of the larger systems (>64 processors) use this type of cache coherence.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] snooping is a process where the individual caches monitor address lines for accesses to memory locations that they have cached.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] For the snooping mechanism, a snoop filter reduces the snooping traffic by maintaining a plurality of entries, each representing a cache line that may be owned by one or more nodes.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] When replacement of one of the entries is required, the snoop filter selects for the replacement of the entry representing the cache line or lines owned by the fewest nodes, as determined from a presence vector in each of the entries.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] A temporal or other type of algorithm is used to refine the selection if more than one cache line is owned by the fewest nodes.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] In a directory-based system, the data being shared is placed in a common directory that maintains the coherence between caches.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] The directory acts as a filter through which the processor must ask permission to load an entry from the primary memory to its cache.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] When an entry is changed, the directory either updates or invalidates the other caches with that entry.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] Distributed shared memory systems mimic these mechanisms in an attempt to maintain consistency between blocks of memory in loosely coupled systems.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] Coherence protocols apply cache coherence in multiprocessor systems.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] The intention is that two clients must never see different values for the same shared data.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] The protocol must implement the basic requirements for coherence.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] It can be tailor-made for the target system or application.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] Protocols can also be classified as snoopy or directory-based.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] Typically, early systems used directory-based protocols where a directory would keep a track of the data being shared and the sharers.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] In snoopy protocols, the transaction requests (to read, write, or upgrade) are sent out to all processors.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] All processors snoop the request and respond appropriately.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] When a write operation is observed to a location that a cache has a copy of, the cache controller invalidates its own copy of the snooped memory location, which forces a read from main memory of the new value on its next access.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] When a write operation is observed to a location that a cache has a copy of, the cache controller updates its own copy of the snooped memory location with the new data.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] If the protocol design states that whenever any copy of the shared data is changed, all the other copies must be "updated" to reflect the change, then it is a write-update protocol.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] If the design states that a write to a cached copy by any processor requires other processors to discard or invalidate their cached copies, then it is a write-invalidate protocol.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] However, scalability is one shortcoming of broadcast protocols.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] Various models and protocols have been devised for maintaining coherence, such as MSI, MESI (aka Illinois), MOSI, MOESI, MERSI, MESIF, write-once, Synapse, Berkeley, Firefly and Dragon protocol.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] In 2011, ARM Ltd proposed the AMBA 4 ACE for handling coherency in SoCs.
[src:caching/cache-coherence] The AMBA CHI (Coherent Hub Interface) specification from ARM Ltd, which belongs to AMBA5 group of specifications defines the interfaces for the connection of fully coherent processors.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] In computing, **cache replacement policies** (also known as **cache replacement algorithms** or **cache algorithms**) are optimizing instructions or algorithms which a computer program or hardware-maintained structure can utilize to manage a cache of information.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Caching improves performance by keeping recent or often-used data items in memory locations which are faster, or computationally cheaper to access, than normal memory stores.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] When the cache is full, the algorithm must choose which items to discard to make room for new data.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] A cache has two primary figures of merit: latency and hit ratio.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] A number of secondary factors also affect cache performance.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] The hit ratio of a cache describes how often a searched-for item is found.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] More efficient replacement strategies track more usage information to improve the hit rate for a given cache size.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] The latency of a cache describes how long after requesting a desired item the cache can return that item when there is a hit.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Faster replacement strategies typically track less usage information—or, with a direct-mapped cache, no information—to reduce the time required to update the information.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Each replacement strategy is a compromise between hit rate and latency.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Hit-rate measurements are typically performed on benchmark applications, and the hit ratio varies by application.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Video and audio streaming applications often have a hit ratio near zero, because each bit of data in the stream is read once (a compulsory miss), used, and then never read or written again.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Many cache algorithms (particularly LRU) allow streaming data to fill the cache, pushing out information which will soon be used again (cache pollution).
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Other factors may be size, length of time to obtain, and expiration.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Depending on cache size, no further caching algorithm to discard items may be needed.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Algorithms also maintain cache coherence when several caches are used for the same data, such as multiple database servers updating a shared data file.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] The most efficient caching algorithm would be to discard information which would not be needed for the longest time; this is known as Bélády's optimal algorithm, optimal replacement policy, or the clairvoyant algorithm.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Since it is generally impossible to predict how far in the future information will be needed, this is unfeasible in practice.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] The practical minimum can be calculated after experimentation, and the effectiveness of a chosen cache algorithm can be compared.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] When a page fault occurs, a set of pages is in memory.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] In the example, the sequence of 5, 0, 1 is accessed by Frame 1, Frame 2, and Frame 3 respectively.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] When 2 is accessed, it replaces value 5 (which is in frame 1, predicting that value 5 will not be accessed in the near future.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Because a general-purpose operating system cannot predict when 5 will be accessed, Bélády's algorithm cannot be implemented there.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Random replacement selects an item and discards it to make space when necessary.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] This algorithm does not require keeping any access history.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] It has been used in ARM processors due to its simplicity, and it allows efficient stochastic simulation.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] With this algorithm, the cache behaves like a FIFO queue; it evicts blocks in the order in which they were added, regardless of how often or how many times they were accessed before.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] The cache behaves like a stack, and unlike a FIFO queue.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] The cache evicts the block added most recently first, regardless of how often or how many times it was accessed before.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Discards least recently used items first.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] This algorithm requires keeping track of what was used and when, which is cumbersome.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] It requires "age bits" for cache lines, and tracks the least recently used cache line based on these age bits.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] When a cache line is used, the age of the other cache lines changes.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] LRU is a family of caching algorithms, that includes 2Q by Theodore Johnson and Dennis Shasha and LRU/K by Pat O'Neil, Betty O'Neil and Gerhard Weikum.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] When A B C D is installed in the blocks with sequence numbers (increment 1 for each new access) and E is accessed, it is a miss and must be installed in a block.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] With the LRU algorithm, E will replace A because A has the lowest rank (A(0)).
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] In the next-to-last step, D is accessed and the sequence number is updated.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] F is then accessed, replacing B – which had the lowest rank, (B(1)).
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Time-aware, least recently used (TLRU) is a variant of LRU designed for when the contents of a cache have a valid lifetime.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] The algorithm is suitable for network cache applications such as information-centric networking (ICN), content delivery networks (CDNs) and distributed networks in general.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] TLRU introduces a term: TTU (time to use), a timestamp of content (or a page) that stipulates the usability time for the content based on its locality and the content publisher.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] TTU provides more control to a local administrator in regulating network storage.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] When content subject to TLRU arrives, a cache node calculates the local TTU based on the TTU assigned by the content publisher.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] The local TTU value is calculated with a locally defined function.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] When the local TTU value is calculated, content replacement is performed on a subset of the total content of the cache node.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] TLRU ensures that less-popular and short-lived content is replaced with incoming content.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Unlike LRU, MRU discards the most recently used items first.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] MRU algorithms are most useful in situations where the older an item is, the more likely it is to be accessed.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] A B C D are placed in the cache, since there is space available.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] At the fifth access (E), the block which held D is replaced with E since this block was used most recently.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] At the next access (to D), C is replaced since it was the block accessed just before D.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] An SLRU cache is divided into two segments: probationary and protected.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Lines in each segment are ordered from most- to least-recently-accessed.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Data from misses is added to the cache at the most-recently-accessed end of the probationary segment.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Hits are removed from where they reside and added to the most-recently-accessed end of the protected segment; lines in the protected segment have been accessed at least twice.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] The size limit of the protected segment is an SLRU parameter which varies according to I/O workload patterns.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] When data must be discarded from the cache, lines are obtained from the LRU end of the probationary segment.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] LRU may be expensive in caches with higher associativity.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Practical hardware usually employs an approximation to achieve similar performance at a lower hardware cost.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] For CPU caches with large associativity (generally > four ways), the implementation cost of LRU becomes prohibitive.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] In many CPU caches, an algorithm that almost always discards one of the least recently used items is sufficient; many CPU designers choose a PLRU algorithm, which only needs one bit per cache item to work.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] PLRU typically has a slightly-worse miss ratio, slightly-better latency, uses slightly less power than LRU, and has a lower overhead than LRU.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Bits work as a binary tree of one-bit pointers which point to a less-recently-used sub-tree.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Following the pointer chain to the leaf node identifies the replacement candidate.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] With an access, all pointers in the chain from the accessed way's leaf node to the root node are set to point to a sub-tree which does not contain the accessed path.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] When there is access to a value (such as A) and it is not in the cache, it is loaded from memory and placed in the block where the arrows are pointing in the example.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] After that block is placed, the arrows are flipped to point the opposite way.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] A, B, C and D are placed; E replaces A as the cache fills because that was where the arrows were pointing, and the arrows which led to A flip to point in the opposite direction (to B, the block which will be replaced on the next cache miss).
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] The LRU algorithm cannot be implemented in the critical path of computer systems, such as operating systems, due to its high overhead; Clock, an approximation of LRU, is commonly used instead.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Clock-Pro is an approximation of LIRS for low-cost implementation in systems.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Clock-Pro has the basic Clock framework, with three advantages.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] It has three "clock hands" (unlike Clock's single "hand"), and can approximately measure the reuse distance of data accesses.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Like LIRS, it can quickly evict one-time-access or low-locality data items.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Clock-Pro is as complex as Clock, and is easy to implement at low cost.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] The buffer-cache replacement implementation in the 2017 version of Linux combines LRU and Clock-Pro.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] The LFU algorithm counts how often an item is needed; those used less often are discarded first.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] This is similar to LRU, except that how many times a block was accessed is stored instead of how recently.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] While running an access sequence, the block which was used the fewest times will be removed from the cache.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] The least frequent recently used (LFRU) algorithm combines the benefits of LFU and LRU.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] LFRU is suitable for network cache applications such as ICN, CDNs, and distributed networks in general.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] In LFRU, the cache is divided into two partitions: privileged and unprivileged.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] The privileged partition is protected; if content is popular, it is pushed into the privileged partition.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] In replacing the privileged partition, LFRU evicts content from the unprivileged partition; pushes content from the privileged to the unprivileged partition, and inserts new content into the privileged partition.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] LRU is used for the privileged partition and an approximated LFU (ALFU) algorithm for the unprivileged partition.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] A variant, LFU with dynamic aging (LFUDA), uses dynamic aging to accommodate shifts in a set of popular objects; it adds a cache-age factor to the reference count when a new object is added to the cache or an existing object is re-referenced.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] LFUDA increments cache age when evicting blocks by setting it to the evicted object's key value, and the cache age is always less than or equal to the minimum key value in the cache.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] If an object was frequently accessed in the past and becomes unpopular, it will remain in the cache for a long time (preventing newly- or less-popular objects from replacing it).
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Dynamic aging reduces the number of such objects, making them eligible for replacement, and LFUDA reduces cache pollution caused by LFU when a cache is small.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] This is a new eviction algorithm designed in 2023.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Compared to existing algorithms, which mostly build on LRU (least-recently-used), S3-FIFO only uses three FIFO queues: a small queue occupying 10% of cache space, a main queue that uses 90% of the cache space, and a ghost queue that only stores object metadata.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] RRIP-style policies are the basis for other cache replacement policies, including Hawkeye.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] RRIP is a flexible policy, proposed by Intel, which attempts to provide good scan resistance while allowing older cache lines that have not been reused to be evicted.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] All cache lines have a prediction value, the RRPV (re-reference prediction value), that should correlate with when the line is expected to be reused.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] The RRPV is usually high on insertion; if a line is not reused soon, it will be evicted to prevent scans (large amounts of data used only once) from filling the cache.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] When a cache line is reused the RRPV is set to zero, indicating that the line has been reused once and is likely to be reused again.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] On a cache miss, the line with an RRPV equal to the maximum possible RRPV is evicted; with 3-bit values, a line with an RRPV of 23 - 1 = 7 is evicted.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] If no lines have this value, all RRPVs in the set are increased by 1 until one reaches it.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] A tie-breaker is needed, and usually, it is the first line on the left.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] The increase is needed to ensure that older lines are aged properly and will be evicted if they are not reused.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] SRRIP inserts lines with an RRPV value of maxRRPV; a line which has just been inserted will be the most likely to be evicted on a cache miss.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] SRRIP performs well normally, but suffers when the working set is much larger than the cache size and causes cache thrashing.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] This is remedied by inserting lines with an RRPV value of maxRRPV most of the time, and inserting lines with an RRPV value of maxRRPV - 1 randomly with a low probability.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] This causes some lines to "stick" in the cache, and helps prevent thrashing.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] BRRIP degrades performance, however, on non-thrashing accesses.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] SRRIP performs best when the working set is smaller than the cache, and BRRIP performs best when the working set is larger than the cache.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] DRRIP uses set dueling to select whether to use SRRIP or BRRIP.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] It dedicates a few sets (typically 32) to use SRRIP and another few to use BRRIP, and uses a policy counter which monitors set performance to determine which policy will be used by the rest of the cache.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Bélády's algorithm is the optimal cache replacement policy, but it requires knowledge of the future to evict lines that will be reused farthest in the future.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] A number of replacement policies have been proposed which attempt to predict future reuse distances from past access patterns, allowing them to approximate the optimal replacement policy.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Some of the best-performing cache replacement policies attempt to imitate Bélády's algorithm.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Hawkeye attempts to emulate Bélády's algorithm by using past accesses by a PC to predict whether the accesses it produces generate cache-friendly (used later) or cache-averse accesses (not used later).
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] It samples a number of non-aligned cache sets, uses a history of length $8\times {\text{the cache size}}$ and emulates Bélády's algorithm on these accesses.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] This allows the policy to determine which lines should have been cached and which should not, predicting whether an instruction is cache-friendly or cache-averse.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] This data is then fed into an RRIP; accesses from cache-friendly instructions have a lower RRPV value (likely to be evicted later), and accesses from cache-averse instructions have a higher RRPV value (likely to be evicted sooner).
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] The RRIP backend makes the eviction decisions.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] The sampled cache and OPT generator set the initial RRPV value of the inserted cache lines.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Hawkeye won the CRC2 cache championship in 2017, and Harmony is an extension of Hawkeye which improves prefetching performance.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Mockingjay tries to improve on Hawkeye in several ways.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] It drops the binary prediction, allowing it to make more fine-grained decisions about which cache lines to evict, and leaves the decision about which cache line to evict for when more information is available.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Mockingjay keeps a sampled cache of unique accesses, the PCs that produced them, and their timestamps.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] When a line in the sampled cache is accessed again, the time difference will be sent to the reuse distance predictor.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] The RDP uses temporal difference learning, where the new RDP value will be increased or decreased by a small number to compensate for outliers; the number is calculated as $w=\min \left(1,{\frac {\text{timestamp difference}}{16}}\right)$ .
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] If the value has not been initialized, the observed reuse distance is inserted directly.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] If the sampled cache is full and a line needs to be discarded, the RDP is instructed that the PC that last accessed it produces streaming accesses.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] On an access or insertion, the estimated time of reuse (ETR) for this line is updated to reflect the predicted reuse distance.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] On a cache miss, the line with the highest ETR value is evicted.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Mockingjay has results which are close to the optimal Bélády's algorithm.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] A number of policies have attempted to use perceptrons, markov chains or other types of machine learning to predict which line to evict.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Learning augmented algorithms also exist for cache replacement.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] LIRS is a page replacement algorithm with better performance than LRU and other, newer replacement algorithms.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Reuse distance is a metric for dynamically ranking accessed pages to make a replacement decision.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] LIRS addresses the limits of LRU by using recency to evaluate inter-reference recency (IRR) to make a replacement decision.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] In the diagram, X indicates that a block is accessed at a particular time.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] If block A1 is accessed at time 1, its recency will be 0; this is the first-accessed block and the IRR will be 1, since it predicts that A1 will be accessed again in time 3.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] In time 2, since A4 is accessed, the recency will become 0 for A4 and 1 for A1; A4 is the most recently accessed object, and the IRR will become 4.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] At time 10, the LIRS algorithm will have two sets: an LIR set = {A1, A2} and an HIR set = {A3, A4, A5}.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] At time 10, if there is access to A4 a miss occurs; LIRS will evict A5 instead of A2 because of its greater recency.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Adaptive replacement cache (ARC) constantly balances between LRU and LFU to improve the combined result.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] It improves SLRU by using information about recently evicted cache items to adjust the size of the protected and probationary segments to make the best use of available cache space.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Clock with adaptive replacement (CAR) combines the advantages of ARC and Clock.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] CAR performs comparably to ARC, and outperforms LRU and Clock.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Like ARC, CAR is self-tuning and requires no user-specified parameters.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] The multi-queue replacement (MQ) algorithm was developed to improve the performance of a second-level buffer cache, such as a server buffer cache, and was introduced in a paper by Zhou, Philbin, and Li.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] The MQ cache contains an *m* number of LRU queues: Q0, Q1, ..., Q*m*-1.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] The value of *m* represents a hierarchy based on the lifetime of all blocks in that queue.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Pannier is a container-based flash caching mechanism which identifies containers whose blocks have variable access patterns.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Pannier has a priority-queue-based survival-queue structure to rank containers based on their survival time, which is proportional to live data in the container.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] Static analysis determines which accesses are cache hits or misses to indicate the worst-case execution time of a program.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] An approach to analyzing properties of LRU caches is to give each block in the cache an "age" (0 for the most recently used) and compute intervals for possible ages.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] This analysis can be refined to distinguish cases where the same program point is accessible by paths that result in misses or hits.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] An efficient analysis may be obtained by abstracting sets of cache states by antichains which are represented by compact binary decision diagrams.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] LRU static analysis does not extend to pseudo-LRU policies.
[src:caching/cache-replacement-policies] According to computational complexity theory, static-analysis problems posed by pseudo-LRU and FIFO are in higher complexity classes than those for LRU.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] In computer science, **consistent hashing** is a special kind of hashing technique such that when a hash table is resized, only $n/m$ keys need to be remapped on average where n is the number of keys and m is the number of slots.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing evenly distributes cache keys across shards, even if some of the shards crash or become unavailable.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] In contrast, in most traditional hash tables, a change in the number of array slots causes nearly all keys to be remapped because the mapping between the keys and the slots is defined by a modular operation.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing is used by Content Delivery Networks because it is useful for distributing requests for content from a rotating population of web servers.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] Tim Berners-Lee credits consistent hashing algorithms, and Daniel Lewin as their inventor, with solving the slashdotting problem which plagued the World Wide Web in the 1990s.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] The term "consistent hashing" was introduced by David Karger *et al.* at MIT for use in distributed caching, particularly for the web.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] This academic paper from 1997 in Symposium on Theory of Computing introduced the term "consistent hashing" as a way of distributing requests among a changing population of web servers.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] Each slot is then represented by a server in a distributed system or cluster.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] The addition of a server and the removal of a server (during scalability or outage) requires only $num\_keys/num\_slots$ items to be re-shuffled when the number of slots (i.e. servers) change.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] The authors mention linear hashing and its ability to handle sequential server addition and removal, while consistent hashing allows servers to be added and removed in an arbitrary order.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] The paper was later re-purposed to address technical challenge of keeping track of a file in peer-to-peer networks such as a distributed hash table.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] Teradata used this technique in their distributed database, released in 1986, although they did not use this term.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] Teradata still uses the concept of a hash table to fulfill exactly this purpose.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] Akamai Technologies was founded in 1998 by the scientists Daniel Lewin and F.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] Thomson Leighton (co-authors of the article coining "consistent hashing").
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] In Akamai's content delivery network, consistent hashing is used to balance the load within a cluster of servers, while a stable marriage algorithm is used to balance load across clusters.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing has also been used to reduce the impact of partial system failures in large web applications to provide robust caching without incurring the system-wide fallout of a failure.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing is also the cornerstone of distributed hash tables (DHTs), which employ hash values to partition a keyspace across a distributed set of nodes, then construct an overlay network of connected nodes that provide efficient node retrieval by key.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] Rendezvous hashing, designed in 1996, is a simpler and more general technique .
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] It achieves the goals of consistent hashing using the very different highest random weight (HRW) algorithm.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] However, when a server is added or removed during outage or scaling (when n changes), all the BLOBs in every server should be reassigned and moved due to rehashing, but this operation is expensive.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing was designed to avoid the problem of having to reassign every BLOB when a server is added or removed throughout the cluster.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] The central idea is to use a hash function that maps both the BLOB and servers to a unit circle, usually $2\pi$ radians.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] For example, $\zeta =\Phi \ \%\ 360$ (where $\Phi$ is hash of a BLOB or server's identifier, like IP address or UUID).
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] Each BLOB is then assigned to the next server that appears on the circle in clockwise order.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] This provides an even distribution of BLOBs to servers.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] But, more importantly, if a server fails and is removed from the circle, only the BLOBs that were mapped to the failed server need to be reassigned to the next server in clockwise order.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] Likewise, if a new server is added, it is added to the unit circle, and only the BLOBs mapped to that server need to be reassigned.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] Importantly, when a server is added or removed, the vast majority of the BLOBs maintain their prior server assignments, and the addition of $n^{th}$ server only causes $1/n$ fraction of the BLOBs to relocate.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] Although the process of moving BLOBs across cache servers in the cluster depends on the context, commonly, the newly added cache server identifies its "predecessor" and moves all the BLOBs, whose mapping belongs to this server (i.e. whose hash value is less than that of the new server), from it.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] However, in the case of web page caches, in most implementations there is no involvement of moving or copying, assuming the cached BLOB is small enough.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] When a request hits a newly added cache server, a cache miss happens and a request to the actual web server is made and the BLOB is cached locally for future requests.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] The redundant BLOBs on the previously used cache servers would be removed as per the cache eviction policies.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] Let $h_{b}(x)$ and $h_{s}(x)$ be the hash functions used for the BLOB and server's unique identifier respectively.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] In practice, a binary search tree (BST) is used to dynamically maintain the ${\text{server ID}}$ within a cluster or hashring, and to find the successor or minimum within the BST, tree traversal is used.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] To avoid skewness of multiple nodes within the radian, which happen due to lack of uniform distribution of the servers within the cluster, multiple labels are used.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] Those duplicate labels are called "virtual nodes" i.e. multiple labels which point to a single "real" label or server within the cluster.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] The amount of virtual nodes or duplicate labels used for a particular server within a cluster is called the "weight" of that particular server.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] A number of extensions to the basic technique are needed for effectively using consistent hashing for load balancing in practice.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] In the basic scheme above, if a server fails, all its BLOBs are reassigned to the next server in clockwise order, potentially doubling the load of that server.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] To ensure a more even redistribution of BLOBs on server failure, each server can be hashed to multiple locations on the unit circle.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] When a server fails, the BLOBs assigned to each of its replicas on the unit circle will get reassigned to a different server in clockwise order, thus redistributing the BLOBs more evenly.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] Another extension concerns a situation where a single BLOB gets "hot" and is accessed a large number of times and will have to be hosted in multiple servers.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] In this situation, the BLOB may be assigned to multiple contiguous servers by traversing the unit circle in clockwise order.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] A more complex practical consideration arises when two BLOBs are hashed near each other in the unit circle and both get "hot" at the same time.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] In this case, both BLOBs will use the same set of contiguous servers in the unit circle.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] This situation can be ameliorated by each BLOB choosing a different hash function for mapping servers to the unit circle.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] Rendezvous hashing, designed in 1996, is a simpler and more general technique, and permits fully distributed agreement on a set of k options out of a possible set of n options.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] It can in fact be shown that consistent hashing is a special case of rendezvous hashing.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] Because of its simplicity and generality, rendezvous hashing is now being used in place of Consistent Hashing in many applications.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] If key values will always increase monotonically, an alternative approach using a hash table with monotonic keys may be more suitable than consistent hashing.
[src:caching/consistent-hashing] The $O(K/N)$ is an average cost for redistribution of keys and the $O(\log N)$ complexity for consistent hashing comes from the fact that a binary search among nodes angles is required to find the next node on the ring.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] A **content delivery network** (**CDN**) or **content distribution network** is a geographically distributed network of proxy servers and corresponding data centers.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] CDNs provide high availability and performance ("speed") through geographical distribution relative to end users, and arose in the late 1990s to alleviate the performance bottlenecks of the Internet as it was becoming a critical medium.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Since then, CDNs have grown to serve a large portion of Internet content, including text, graphics and scripts, downloadable objects (media files, software, and documents), applications (e-commerce, portals), live streaming media, on-demand streaming media, and social media services.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] CDNs are a layer in the internet ecosystem.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Content owners such as media companies and e-commerce vendors pay CDN operators to deliver their content to their end users.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] In turn, a CDN pays Internet service providers (ISPs), carriers, and network operators for hosting its servers in their data centers.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] CDN vendors may cross over into other industries like security, DDoS protection and web application firewalls (WAF), and WAN optimization.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Content delivery service providers include Akamai Technologies, Cloudflare, Amazon CloudFront, Qwilt (Cisco), Fastly, CDN77, BunnyCDN, EdgeNext, and Google Cloud CDN.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] CDN nodes are usually deployed in multiple locations, often over multiple Internet backbones.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Benefits include reducing bandwidth costs, improving page load times, and increasing the global availability of content.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] The number of nodes and servers making up a CDN varies, depending on the architecture, some reaching thousands of nodes with tens of thousands of servers on many remote points of presence (PoPs).
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Others build a global network and have a small number of geographical PoPs.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Requests for content are typically algorithmically directed to nodes that are optimal in some way.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for performance, locations that are best for serving content to the user may be chosen.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] This may be measured by choosing locations that are the fewest hops or the shortest time to the requesting client, or the highest server performance, to optimize delivery across local networks.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for cost, locations that are the least expensive may be chosen instead.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] In an optimal scenario, these two goals tend to align, as **edge servers** that are close to the end user at the edge of the network may have an advantage in performance and cost.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Most CDN providers will provide their services over a varying, defined, set of PoPs, depending on the coverage desired, such as United States, Asia-Pacific, International or Global, etc.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] These sets of PoPs can be called "edges", "edge nodes", "edge servers", or "edge networks" as they would be the closest edge of CDN assets to the end user.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] CDN providers profit either from direct fees paid by content providers using their network, or profit from the user analytics and tracking data collected as their scripts are being loaded onto customers' websites inside their browser origin.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] As such these services are being pointed out as potential privacy intrusions for the purpose of behavioral targeting and solutions are being created to restore single-origin serving and caching of resources.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] In particular, a website using a CDN may violate the EU's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] For example, in 2021 a German court forbade the use of a CDN on a university website, because this caused the transmission of the user's IP address to the CDN, which violated the GDPR.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] CDNs serving JavaScript have also been targeted as a way to inject malicious content into pages using them.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Subresource Integrity mechanism was created in response to ensure that the page loads a script whose content is known and constrained to a hash referenced by the website author.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] The Internet was designed according to the end-to-end principle.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] This principle keeps the core network relatively simple and moves the intelligence as much as possible to the network end-points: the hosts and clients.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] As a result, the core network is specialized, optimized, and simplified to only forward data packets.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Content Delivery Networks extend the transport network by distributing on it a variety of intelligent applications employing techniques designed to optimize content delivery.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] The resulting tightly integrated overlay uses web caching, server-load balancing, request routing, and content services.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Web caches store popular content on servers that have the greatest demand for the content requested.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] These shared network appliances reduce bandwidth requirements, reduce server load, and improve the client response times for content stored in the cache.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Web caches are populated based on requests from users (pull caching) or based on preloaded content disseminated from content servers (push caching).
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Server-load balancing uses one or more techniques including service-based (global load balancing) or hardware-based (i.e. layer 4–7 switches, also known as a web switch, content switch, or multilayer switch) to share traffic among a number of servers or web caches.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Here the switch is assigned a single virtual IP address.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Traffic arriving at the switch is then directed to one of the real web servers attached to the switch.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] This has the advantage of balancing load, increasing total capacity, improving scalability, and providing increased reliability by redistributing the load of a failed web server and providing server health checks.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] A content cluster or service node can be formed using a layer 4–7 switch to balance load across a number of servers or a number of web caches within the network.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Request routing directs client requests to the content source best able to serve the request.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] This may involve directing a client request to the service node that is closest to the client, or to the one with the most capacity.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] A variety of algorithms are used to route the request.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] These include Global Server Load Balancing, DNS-based request routing, Dynamic metafile generation, HTML rewriting, and anycasting.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Proximity—choosing the closest service node—is estimated using a variety of techniques including reactive probing, proactive probing, and connection monitoring.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] CDNs use a variety of methods of content delivery including, but not limited to, manual asset copying, active web caches, and global hardware load balancers.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Several protocol suites are designed to provide access to a wide variety of content services distributed throughout a content network.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] The Internet Content Adaptation Protocol (ICAP) was developed in the late 1990s to provide an open standard for connecting application servers.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] A more recently defined and robust solution is provided by the Open Pluggable Edge Services (OPES) protocol.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] This architecture defines OPES service applications that can reside on the OPES processor itself or be executed remotely on a Callout Server.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Edge Side Includes or ESI is a small markup language for edge-level dynamic web content assembly.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] It is fairly common for websites to have generated content.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] It could be because of changing content like catalogs or forums, or because of the personalization.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] This creates a problem for caching systems.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] To overcome this problem, a group of companies created ESI.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] In *peer-to-peer (P2P)* content-delivery networks, clients provide resources as well as use them.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] This means that, unlike client–server systems, the content-centric networks can actually perform better as more users begin to access the content (especially with protocols such as Bittorrent that require users to share).
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] This property is one of the major advantages of using P2P networks because it makes the setup and running costs very small for the original content distributor.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] To incentive peers to participate in the P2P network, web3 and blockchain technologies can be used: participating nodes receive crypto tokens in exchange of their involvement.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] If content owners are not satisfied with the options or costs of a commercial CDN service, they can create their own CDN.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] A private CDN consists of PoPs (points of presence) that are only serving content for their owner.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] These PoPs can be caching servers, reverse proxies or application delivery controllers.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] It can be as simple as two caching servers, or large enough to serve petabytes of content.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] When a private CDN is deployed within a company network, it is also referred as Entreprise CDN or **eCDN**.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Large content distribution networks may even build and set up their own private network to distribute copies of content across cache locations.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Such private networks are usually used in conjunction with public networks as a backup option in case the capacity of the private network is not enough or there is a failure which leads to capacity reduction.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Since the same content has to be distributed across many locations, a variety of multicasting techniques may be used to reduce bandwidth consumption.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Over private networks, it has also been proposed to select multicast trees according to network load conditions to more efficiently utilize available network capacity.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] The rapid growth of streaming video traffic required large capital expenditures by broadband providers in order to meet this demand and retain subscribers by delivering a sufficiently good quality of experience.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] To address this, telecommunications service providers have begun to launch their own content delivery networks as a means to lessen the demands on the network backbone and reduce infrastructure investments.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Because they own the networks over which video content is transmitted, telco CDNs have advantages over traditional CDNs.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] They own the last mile and can deliver content closer to the end-user because it can be cached deep in their networks.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] This deep caching minimizes the distance that video data travels over the general Internet and delivers it more quickly and reliably.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Telco CDNs also have a built-in cost advantage since traditional CDNs must lease bandwidth from them and build the operator's margin into their own cost model.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] In addition, by operating their own content delivery infrastructure, telco operators have better control over the utilization of their resources.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Content management operations performed by CDNs are usually applied without (or with very limited) information about the network (e.g., topology, utilization etc.) of the telco-operators with which they interact or have business relationships.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] These pose a number of challenges for the telco-operators who have a limited sphere of action in face of the impact of these operations on the utilization of their resources.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] In contrast, the deployment of telco-CDNs allows operators to implement their own content management operations, which enables them to have a better control over the utilization of their resources and, as such, provide better quality of service and experience to their end users.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] In June 2011, StreamingMedia.com reported that a group of TSPs had founded an Operator Carrier Exchange (OCX) to interconnect their networks and compete more directly against large traditional CDNs like Akamai and Limelight Networks, which have extensive PoPs worldwide.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] This way, telcos are building a Federated CDN offering, which is more interesting for a content provider willing to deliver its content to the aggregated audience of this federation.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] It is likely that in a near future, other telco CDN federations will be created.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] They will grow by enrollment of new telcos joining the federation and bringing network presence and their Internet subscriber bases to the existing ones.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] The Open Caching specification by Streaming Video Technology Alliance defines a set of APIs that allows a Content Provider to deliver its content using several CDNs in a consistent way, seeing each CDN provider the same way through these APIs.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Combining several CDN services allow Content Providers to not rely on a single CDN service, especially concerned to deal with high peak audience during live events.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] There are several ways to allocate traffic to a particular CDN among the list, either client-side CDN selection, or server-side (at the Content Provider's origin) or cloud-side (in the middle, between the content origin and the audience).
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] CDN selection criteria can be performance, availability and cost.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Traditionally, CDNs have used the IP of the client's recursive DNS resolver to geo-locate the client.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] While this is a sound approach in many situations, this leads to poor client performance if the client uses a non-local recursive DNS resolver that is far away.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] For instance, a CDN may route requests from a client in India to its edge server in Singapore, if that client uses a public DNS resolver in Singapore, causing poor performance for that client.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Indeed, a recent study showed that in many countries where public DNS resolvers are in popular use, the median distance between the clients and their recursive DNS resolvers can be as high as a thousand miles.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] In August 2011, a global consortium of leading Internet service providers led by Google announced their official implementation of the edns-client-subnet IETF Internet Draft, which is intended to accurately localize DNS resolution responses.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] The initiative involves a limited number of leading DNS service providers, such as Google Public DNS, and CDN service providers as well.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] With the edns-client-subnet EDNS0 option, CDNs can now utilize the IP address of the requesting client's subnet when resolving DNS requests.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] This approach, called end-user mapping, has been adopted by CDNs and it has been shown to drastically reduce the round-trip latencies and improve performance for clients who use public DNS or other non-local resolvers.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] However, the use of EDNS0 also has drawbacks as it decreases the effectiveness of caching resolutions at the recursive resolvers, increases the total DNS resolution traffic, and raises a privacy concern of exposing the client's subnet.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Virtualization technologies are being used to deploy virtual CDNs (vCDNs) (also known as a software-defined CDN or sd-CDN) with the goal to reduce content provider costs, and at the same time, increase elasticity and decrease service delay.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] With vCDNs, it is possible to avoid traditional CDN limitations, such as performance, reliability and availability since virtual caches are deployed dynamically (as virtual machines or containers) in physical servers distributed across the provider's geographical coverage.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] As the virtual cache placement is based on both the content type and server or end-user geographic location, the vCDNs have a significant impact on service delivery and network congestion.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] To boost performance, delivery to clients from servers can use alternate non-HTTP protocols such as WebRTC and WebSockets.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] In 2017, Addy Osmani of Google started referring to software solutions that could integrate naturally with the Responsive Web Design paradigm (with particular reference to the <picture> element) as **Image CDN**s.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] The expression referred to the ability of a web architecture to serve multiple versions of the same image through HTTP, depending on the properties of the browser requesting it, as determined by either the browser or the server-side logic.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] The purpose of Image CDNs was, in Google's vision, to serve high-quality images (or, better, images perceived as high-quality by the human eye) while preserving download speed, thus contributing to a great User experience (UX).
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Arguably, the *Image CDN* term was originally a misnomer, as neither Cloudinary nor Imgix (the examples quoted by Google in the 2017 guide by Addy Osmani) were, at the time, a CDN in the classical sense of the term.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Shortly afterwards, though, several companies offered solutions that allowed developers to serve different versions of their graphical assets according to several strategies.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] Many of these solutions were built on top of traditional CDNs, such as Akamai, CloudFront, Fastly, Edgecast and Cloudflare.
[src:caching/content-delivery-network] At the same time, other solutions that already provided an image multi-serving service joined the Image CDN definition by either offering CDN functionality natively (ImageEngine) or integrating with one of the existing CDNs (Cloudinary/Akamai, Imgix/Fastly).
[src:caching/hash-function] A **hash function** is any function that can be used to map data of arbitrary size to fixed-size values, though there are some hash functions that support variable-length output.
[src:caching/hash-function] The values returned by a hash function are called *hash values*, *hash codes*, (*hash/message*) *digests*, or simply *hashes*.
[src:caching/hash-function] The values are usually used to index a fixed-size table called a *hash table*.
[src:caching/hash-function] Use of a hash function to index a hash table is called *hashing* or *scatter-storage addressing*.
[src:caching/hash-function] Hash functions and their associated hash tables are used in data storage and retrieval applications to access data in a small and nearly constant time per retrieval.
[src:caching/hash-function] They require an amount of storage space only fractionally greater than the total space required for the data or records themselves.
[src:caching/hash-function] Hashing is a way to access data quickly and efficiently.
[src:caching/hash-function] Unlike lists or trees, it provides near-constant access time.
[src:caching/hash-function] It also uses much less storage than trying to store all possible keys directly, especially when keys are large or variable in length.
[src:caching/hash-function] Use of hash functions relies on statistical properties of key and function interaction: worst-case behavior is intolerably bad but rare, and average-case behavior can be nearly optimal (minimal collision).
[src:caching/hash-function] Hash functions are related to (and often confused with) checksums, check digits, fingerprints, lossy compression, randomization functions, error-correcting codes, and ciphers.
[src:caching/hash-function] Although the concepts overlap to some extent, each one has its own uses and requirements and is designed and optimized differently.
[src:caching/hash-function] The hash function differs from these concepts mainly in terms of data integrity.
[src:caching/hash-function] Hash tables may use non-cryptographic hash functions, while cryptographic hash functions are used in cybersecurity to secure sensitive data such as passwords.
[src:caching/hash-function] In a hash table, a hash function takes a key as an input, which is associated with a datum or record and used to identify it to the data storage and retrieval application.
[src:caching/hash-function] The keys may be fixed-length, like an integer, or variable-length, like a name.
[src:caching/hash-function] In some cases, the key is the datum itself.
[src:caching/hash-function] The output is a hash code used to index a hash table holding the data or records, or pointers to them.
[src:caching/hash-function] A good hash function satisfies two basic properties: it should be very fast to compute, and it should minimize duplication of output values (collisions).
[src:caching/hash-function] Hash functions rely on generating favorable probability distributions for their effectiveness, reducing access time to nearly constant.
[src:caching/hash-function] High table loading factors, pathological key sets, and poorly designed hash functions can result in access times approaching linear in the number of items in the table.
[src:caching/hash-function] Hash functions can be designed to give the best worst-case performance, good performance under high table loading factors, and in special cases, perfect (collisionless) mapping of keys into hash codes.
[src:caching/hash-function] Implementation is based on parity-preserving bit operations (XOR and ADD), multiply, or divide.
[src:caching/hash-function] A necessary adjunct to the hash function is a collision-resolution method that employs an auxiliary data structure like linked lists, or systematic probing of the table to find an empty slot.
[src:caching/hash-function] Hash functions are used in conjunction with hash tables to store and retrieve data items or data records.
[src:caching/hash-function] The hash function translates the key associated with each datum or record into a hash code, which is used to index the hash table.
[src:caching/hash-function] When an item is to be added to the table, the hash code may index an empty slot (also called a bucket), in which case the item is added to the table there.
[src:caching/hash-function] If the hash code indexes a full slot, then some kind of collision resolution is required: the new item may be omitted (not added to the table), or replace the old item, or be added to the table in some other location by a specified procedure.
[src:caching/hash-function] That procedure depends on the structure of the hash table.
[src:caching/hash-function] In *chained hashing*, each slot is the head of a linked list or chain, and items that collide at the slot are added to the chain.
[src:caching/hash-function] Chains may be kept in random order and searched linearly, or in serial order, or as a self-ordering list by frequency to speed up access.
[src:caching/hash-function] In *open address hashing*, the table is probed starting from the occupied slot in a specified manner, usually by linear probing, quadratic probing, or double hashing until an open slot is located or the entire table is probed (overflow).
[src:caching/hash-function] Searching for the item follows the same procedure until the item is located, an open slot is found, or the entire table has been searched (item not in table).
[src:caching/hash-function] Hash functions are also used to build caches for large data sets stored in slow media.
[src:caching/hash-function] A cache is generally simpler than a hashed search table, since any collision can be resolved by discarding or writing back the older of the two colliding items.
[src:caching/hash-function] Hash functions are an essential ingredient of the Bloom filter, a space-efficient probabilistic data structure that is used to test whether an element is a member of a set.
[src:caching/hash-function] A special case of hashing is known as geometric hashing or the *grid method*.
[src:caching/hash-function] In these applications, the set of all inputs is some sort of metric space, and the hashing function can be interpreted as a partition of that space into a grid of *cells*.
[src:caching/hash-function] The table is often an array with two or more indices (called a *grid file*, *grid index*, *bucket grid*, and similar names), and the hash function returns an index tuple.
[src:caching/hash-function] Hash tables are also used to implement associative arrays and dynamic sets.
[src:caching/hash-function] A good hash function should map the expected inputs as evenly as possible over its output range.
[src:caching/hash-function] That is, every hash value in the output range should be generated with roughly the same probability.
[src:caching/hash-function] The reason for this requirement is that the cost of hashing-based methods goes up sharply as the number of *collisions* — pairs of inputs that are mapped to the same hash value — increases.
[src:caching/hash-function] If some hash values are more likely to occur than others, then a larger fraction of the lookup operations will have to search through a larger set of colliding table entries.
[src:caching/hash-function] This criterion only requires the value to be *uniformly distributed*, not *random* in any sense.
[src:caching/hash-function] A good randomizing function is (barring computational efficiency concerns) generally a good choice as a hash function, but the converse need not be true.
[src:caching/hash-function] Hash tables often contain only a small subset of the valid inputs.
[src:caching/hash-function] For instance, a club membership list may contain only a hundred or so member names, out of the very large set of all possible names.
[src:caching/hash-function] In these cases, the uniformity criterion should hold for almost all typical subsets of entries that may be found in the table, not just for the global set of all possible entries.
[src:caching/hash-function] In other words, if a typical set of *m* records is hashed to *n* table slots, then the probability of a bucket receiving many more than *m*/*n* records should be vanishingly small.
[src:caching/hash-function] In particular, if *m* < *n*, then very few buckets should have more than one or two records.
[src:caching/hash-function] A small number of collisions is virtually inevitable, even if *n* is much larger than *m*—see the birthday problem.
[src:caching/hash-function] In special cases when the keys are known in advance and the key set is static, a hash function can be found that achieves absolute (or collisionless) uniformity.
[src:caching/hash-function] Such a hash function is said to be *perfect*.
[src:caching/hash-function] There is no algorithmic way of constructing such a function—searching for one is a factorial function of the number of keys to be mapped versus the number of table slots that they are mapped into.
[src:caching/hash-function] When testing a hash function, the uniformity of the distribution of hash values can be evaluated by the chi-squared test.
[src:caching/hash-function] This test is a goodness-of-fit measure: it is the actual distribution of items in buckets versus the expected (or uniform) distribution of items.
[src:caching/hash-function] where n is the number of keys, m is the number of buckets, and *b**j* is the number of items in bucket j.
[src:caching/hash-function] A ratio within one confidence interval (such as 0.95 to 1.05) is indicative that the hash function evaluated has an expected uniform distribution.
[src:caching/hash-function] Hash functions can have some technical properties that make it more likely that they will have a uniform distribution when applied.
[src:caching/hash-function] One is the strict avalanche criterion: whenever a single input bit is complemented, each of the output bits changes with a 50% probability.
[src:caching/hash-function] The reason for this property is that selected subsets of the keyspace may have low variability.
[src:caching/hash-function] For the output to be uniformly distributed, a low amount of variability, even one bit, should translate into a high amount of variability (i.e. distribution over the tablespace) in the output.
[src:caching/hash-function] Each bit should change with a probability of 50% because, if some bits are reluctant to change, then the keys become clustered around those values.
[src:caching/hash-function] If the bits want to change too readily, then the mapping is approaching a fixed XOR function of a single bit.
[src:caching/hash-function] Standard tests for this property have been described in the literature.
[src:caching/hash-function] The relevance of the criterion to a multiplicative hash function is assessed here.
[src:caching/hash-function] In data storage and retrieval applications, the use of a hash function is a trade-off between search time and data storage space.
[src:caching/hash-function] If search time were unbounded, then a very compact unordered linear list would be the best medium; if storage space were unbounded, then a randomly accessible structure indexable by the key-value would be very large and very sparse, but very fast.
[src:caching/hash-function] A hash function takes a finite amount of time to map a potentially large keyspace to a feasible amount of storage space searchable in a bounded amount of time regardless of the number of keys.
[src:caching/hash-function] In most applications, the hash function should be computable with minimum latency and secondarily in a minimum number of instructions.
[src:caching/hash-function] Computational complexity varies with the number of instructions required and latency of individual instructions, with the simplest being the bitwise methods (folding), followed by the multiplicative methods, and the most complex (slowest) are the division-based methods.
[src:caching/hash-function] Because collisions should be infrequent, and cause a marginal delay but are otherwise harmless, it is usually preferable to choose a faster hash function over one that needs more computation but saves a few collisions.
[src:caching/hash-function] Division-based implementations can be of particular concern because a division requires multiple cycles on nearly all processor microarchitectures.
[src:caching/hash-function] Division (modulo) by a constant can be inverted to become a multiplication by the word-size multiplicative-inverse of that constant.
[src:caching/hash-function] This can be done by the programmer, or by the compiler.
[src:caching/hash-function] Division can also be reduced directly into a series of shift-subtracts and shift-adds, though minimizing the number of such operations required is a daunting problem; the number of machine-language instructions resulting may be more than a dozen and swamp the pipeline.
[src:caching/hash-function] If the microarchitecture has hardware multiply functional units, then the multiply-by-inverse is likely a better approach.
[src:caching/hash-function] We can allow the table size *n* to not be a power of 2 and still not have to perform any remainder or division operation, as these computations are sometimes costly.
[src:caching/hash-function] For example, let *n* be significantly less than 2*b*.
[src:caching/hash-function] Consider a pseudorandom number generator function *P*(key) that is uniform on the interval [0, 2*b* − 1].
[src:caching/hash-function] A hash function uniform on the interval [0, *n* − 1] is *n* *P*(key) / 2*b*.
[src:caching/hash-function] We can replace the division by a (possibly faster) right bit shift: *n P*(key) >> *b*.
[src:caching/hash-function] If keys are being hashed repeatedly, and the hash function is costly, then computing time can be saved by precomputing the hash codes and storing them with the keys.
[src:caching/hash-function] Matching hash codes almost certainly means that the keys are identical.
[src:caching/hash-function] This technique is used for the transposition table in game-playing programs, which stores a 64-bit hashed representation of the board position.
[src:caching/hash-function] A *universal hashing* scheme is a randomized algorithm that selects a hash function *h* among a family of such functions, in such a way that the probability of a collision of any two distinct keys is 1/*m*, where *m* is the number of distinct hash values desired—independently of the two keys.
[src:caching/hash-function] Universal hashing ensures (in a probabilistic sense) that the hash function application will behave as well as if it were using a random function, for any distribution of the input data.
[src:caching/hash-function] It will, however, have more collisions than perfect hashing and may require more operations than a special-purpose hash function.
[src:caching/hash-function] A hash function that allows only certain table sizes or strings only up to a certain length, or cannot accept a seed (i.e. allow double hashing) is less useful than one that does.
[src:caching/hash-function] A hash function is applicable in a variety of situations.
[src:caching/hash-function] A hash procedure must be deterministic—for a given input value, it must always generate the same hash value.
[src:caching/hash-function] In other words, it must be a function of the data to be hashed, in the mathematical sense of the term.
[src:caching/hash-function] This requirement excludes hash functions that depend on external variable parameters, such as pseudo-random number generators or the time of day.
[src:caching/hash-function] It also excludes functions that depend on the memory address of the object being hashed, because the address may change during execution (as may happen on systems that use certain methods of garbage collection), although sometimes rehashing of the item is possible.
[src:caching/hash-function] The determinism is in the context of the reuse of the function.
[src:caching/hash-function] For example, Python adds the feature that hash functions make use of a randomized seed that is generated once when the Python process starts in addition to the input to be hashed.
[src:caching/hash-function] The Python hash (SipHash) is still a valid hash function when used within a single run, but if the values are persisted (for example, written to disk), they can no longer be treated as valid hash values, since in the next run the random value might differ.
[src:caching/hash-function] It is often desirable that the output of a hash function have fixed size (but see below).
[src:caching/hash-function] If, for example, the output is constrained to 32-bit integer values, then the hash values can be used to index into an array.
[src:caching/hash-function] Such hashing is commonly used to accelerate data searches.
[src:caching/hash-function] Producing fixed-length output from variable-length input can be accomplished by breaking the input data into chunks of specific size.
[src:caching/hash-function] Hash functions used for data searches use some arithmetic expression that iteratively processes chunks of the input (such as the characters in a string) to produce the hash value.
[src:caching/hash-function] In many applications, the range of hash values may be different for each run of the program or may change along the same run (for instance, when a hash table needs to be expanded).
[src:caching/hash-function] In those situations, one needs a hash function which takes two parameters—the input data *z*, and the number *n* of allowed hash values.
[src:caching/hash-function] A common solution is to compute a fixed hash function with a very large range (say, 0 to 232 − 1), divide the result by *n*, and use the division's remainder.
[src:caching/hash-function] If *n* is itself a power of 2, this can be done by bit masking and bit shifting.
[src:caching/hash-function] When this approach is used, the hash function must be chosen so that the result has fairly uniform distribution between 0 and *n* − 1, for any value of *n* that may occur in the application.
[src:caching/hash-function] Depending on the function, the remainder may be uniform only for certain values of *n*, e.g. odd or prime numbers.
[src:caching/hash-function] When the hash function is used to store values in a hash table that outlives the run of the program, and the hash table needs to be expanded or shrunk, the hash table is referred to as a dynamic hash table.
[src:caching/hash-function] A hash function that will relocate the minimum number of records when the table is resized is desirable.
[src:caching/hash-function] What is needed is a hash function *H*(*z*,*n*) (where *z* is the key being hashed and *n* is the number of allowed hash values) such that *H*(*z*,*n* + 1) = *H*(*z*,*n*) with probability close to *n*/(*n* + 1).
[src:caching/hash-function] Linear hashing and spiral hashing are examples of dynamic hash functions that execute in constant time but relax the property of uniformity to achieve the minimal movement property.
[src:caching/hash-function] Extendible hashing uses a dynamic hash function that requires space proportional to *n* to compute the hash function, and it becomes a function of the previous keys that have been inserted.
[src:caching/hash-function] Several algorithms that preserve the uniformity property but require time proportional to *n* to compute the value of *H*(*z*,*n*) have been invented.
[src:caching/hash-function] A hash function with minimal movement is especially useful in distributed hash tables.
[src:caching/hash-function] In some applications, the input data may contain features that are irrelevant for comparison purposes.
[src:caching/hash-function] For example, when looking up a personal name, it may be desirable to ignore the distinction between upper and lower case letters.
[src:caching/hash-function] For such data, one must use a hash function that is compatible with the data equivalence criterion being used: that is, any two inputs that are considered equivalent must yield the same hash value.
[src:caching/hash-function] This can be accomplished by normalizing the input before hashing it, as by upper-casing all letters.
[src:caching/hash-function] There are several common algorithms for hashing integers.
[src:caching/hash-function] The method giving the best distribution is data-dependent.
[src:caching/hash-function] One of the simplest and most common methods in practice is the modulo division method.
[src:caching/hash-function] If the data to be hashed is small enough, then one can use the data itself (reinterpreted as an integer) as the hashed value.
[src:caching/hash-function] The cost of computing this *identity* hash function is effectively zero.
[src:caching/hash-function] This hash function is perfect, as it maps each input to a distinct hash value.
[src:caching/hash-function] The meaning of "small enough" depends on the size of the type that is used as the hashed value.
[src:caching/hash-function] For example, in Java, the hash code is a 32-bit integer.
[src:caching/hash-function] Thus the 32-bit integer `Integer` and 32-bit floating-point `Float` objects can simply use the value directly, whereas the 64-bit integer `Long` and 64-bit floating-point `Double` cannot.
[src:caching/hash-function] Other types of data can also use this hashing scheme.
[src:caching/hash-function] For example, when mapping character strings between upper and lower case, one can use the binary encoding of each character, interpreted as an integer, to index a table that gives the alternative form of that character ("A" for "a", "8" for "8", etc.).
[src:caching/hash-function] If each character is stored in 8 bits (as in extended ASCII or ISO Latin 1), the table has only 28 = 256 entries; in the case of Unicode characters, the table would have 17 × 216 = 1114112 entries.
[src:caching/hash-function] The same technique can be used to map two-letter country codes like "us" or "za" to country names (262 = 676 table entries), 5-digit ZIP codes like 13083 to city names (100000 entries), etc.
[src:caching/hash-function] Invalid data values (such as the country code "xx" or the ZIP code 00000) may be left undefined in the table or mapped to some appropriate "null" value.
[src:caching/hash-function] If the keys are uniformly or sufficiently uniformly distributed over the key space, so that the key values are essentially random, then they may be considered to be already "hashed".
[src:caching/hash-function] In this case, any number of any bits in the key may be extracted and collated as an index into the hash table.
[src:caching/hash-function] For example, a simple hash function might mask off the m least significant bits and use the result as an index into a hash table of size 2*m*.
[src:caching/hash-function] A mid-squares hash code is produced by squaring the input and extracting an appropriate number of middle digits or bits.
[src:caching/hash-function] For example, if the input is 123456789 and the hash table size 10000, then squaring the key produces 15241578750190521, so the hash code is taken as the middle 4 digits of the 17-digit number (ignoring the high digit) 8750.
[src:caching/hash-function] The mid-squares method produces a reasonable hash code if there is not a lot of leading or trailing zeros in the key.
[src:caching/hash-function] This is a variant of multiplicative hashing, but not as good because an arbitrary key is not a good multiplier.
[src:caching/hash-function] A standard technique is to use a modulo function on the key, by selecting a divisor M which is a prime number close to the table size, so *h*(*K*) ≡ *K* (mod *M*).
[src:caching/hash-function] This gives a distribution from {0, *M* − 1}.
[src:caching/hash-function] This gives good results over a large number of key sets.
[src:caching/hash-function] A significant drawback of division hashing is that division requires multiple cycles on most modern architectures (including x86) and can be 10 times slower than multiplication.
[src:caching/hash-function] A second drawback is that it will not break up clustered keys.
[src:caching/hash-function] This technique works well in practice because many key sets are sufficiently random already, and the probability that a key set will be cyclical by a large prime number is small.
[src:caching/hash-function] Algebraic coding is a variant of the division method of hashing which uses division by a polynomial modulo 2 instead of an integer to map n bits to m bits.
[src:caching/hash-function] If *Z*(*x*) is constructed to have t or fewer non-zero coefficients, then keys which share fewer than t bits are guaranteed to not collide.
[src:caching/hash-function] Z is a function of k, t, and n (the last of which is a divisor of 2*k* − 1) and is constructed from the finite field GF(2*k*).
[src:caching/hash-function] Define $P(x)=\prod _{j\in S}(x-\alpha ^{j})$ where α ∈*n* GF(2*k*) and where the coefficients of *P*(*x*) are computed in this field.
[src:caching/hash-function] Since α2*j* is a root of *P*(*x*) whenever α*j* is a root, it follows that the coefficients *pi* of *P*(*x*) satisfy *p*2 *i* = *p*i, so they are all 0 or 1.
[src:caching/hash-function] If *R*(*x*) = *r**n*−1*x**n*−1 + ⋯ + *r*1*x* + *r*0 is any nonzero polynomial modulo 2 with at most t nonzero coefficients, then *R*(*x*) is not a multiple of *P*(*x*) modulo 2.
[src:caching/hash-function] If follows that the corresponding hash function will map keys with fewer than t bits in common to unique indices.
[src:caching/hash-function] The usual outcome is that either n will get large, or t will get large, or both, for the scheme to be computationally feasible.
[src:caching/hash-function] Therefore, it is more suited to hardware or microcode implementation.
[src:caching/hash-function] Unique permutation hashing has a guaranteed best worst-case insertion time.
[src:caching/hash-function] Standard multiplicative hashing uses the formula *h**a*(*K*) = ⌊(*aK* mod *W*) / (*W*/*M*)⌋, which produces a hash value in {0, …, *M* − 1}.
[src:caching/hash-function] The value a is an appropriately chosen value that should be relatively prime to W; it should be large, and its binary representation a random mix of 1s and 0s.
[src:caching/hash-function] An important practical special case occurs when *W* = 2*w* and *M* = 2*m* are powers of 2 and w is the machine word size.
[src:caching/hash-function] and for fixed m and w this translates into a single integer multiplication and right-shift, making it one of the fastest hash functions to compute.
[src:caching/hash-function] Multiplicative hashing is susceptible to a "common mistake" that leads to poor diffusion—higher-value input bits do not affect lower-value output bits.
[src:caching/hash-function] A transmutation on the input which shifts the span of retained top bits down and XORs or ADDs them to the key before the multiplication step corrects for this.
[src:caching/hash-function] Fibonacci hashing is a form of multiplicative hashing in which the multiplier is 2*w* / ϕ, where w is the machine word length and ϕ (phi) is the golden ratio (approximately 1.618).
[src:caching/hash-function] A property of this multiplier is that it uniformly distributes over the table space, blocks of consecutive keys with respect to any block of bits in the key.
[src:caching/hash-function] Consecutive keys within the high bits or low bits of the key (or some other field) are relatively common.
[src:caching/hash-function] The multiplier should be odd, so the least significant bit of the output is invertible modulo 2*w*.
[src:caching/hash-function] The last two values given above are rounded (up and down, respectively) by more than 1/2 of a least-significant bit to achieve this.
[src:caching/hash-function] Zobrist hashing was originally introduced as a means of compactly representing chess positions in computer game-playing programs.
[src:caching/hash-function] A unique random number was assigned to represent each type of piece (six each for black and white) on each space of the board.
[src:caching/hash-function] Thus a table of 64×12 such numbers is initialized at the start of the program.
[src:caching/hash-function] The random numbers could be any length, but 64 bits was natural due to the 64 squares on the board.
[src:caching/hash-function] A position was transcribed by cycling through the pieces in a position, indexing the corresponding random numbers (vacant spaces were not included in the calculation) and XORing them together (the starting value could be 0 (the identity value for XOR) or a random seed).
[src:caching/hash-function] The resulting value was reduced by modulo, folding, or some other operation to produce a hash table index.
[src:caching/hash-function] The original Zobrist hash was stored in the table as the representation of the position.
[src:caching/hash-function] Later, the method was extended to hashing integers by representing each byte in each of 4 possible positions in the word by a unique 32-bit random number.
[src:caching/hash-function] Thus, a table of 28×4 random numbers is constructed.
[src:caching/hash-function] A 32-bit hashed integer is transcribed by successively indexing the table with the value of each byte of the plain text integer and XORing the loaded values together (again, the starting value can be the identity value or a random seed).
[src:caching/hash-function] The natural extension to 64-bit integers is by use of a table of 28×8 64-bit random numbers.
[src:caching/hash-function] This kind of function has some nice theoretical properties, one of which is called *3-tuple independence*, meaning that every 3-tuple of keys is equally likely to be mapped to any 3-tuple of hash values.
[src:caching/hash-function] A hash function can be designed to exploit existing entropy in the keys.
[src:caching/hash-function] If the keys have leading or trailing zeros, or particular fields that are unused, always zero or some other constant, or generally vary little, then masking out only the volatile bits and hashing on those will provide a better and possibly faster hash function.
[src:caching/hash-function] Selected divisors or multipliers in the division and multiplicative schemes may make more uniform hash functions if the keys are cyclic or have other redundancies.
[src:caching/hash-function] When the data values are long (or variable-length) character strings—such as personal names, web page addresses, or mail messages—their distribution is usually very uneven, with complicated dependencies.
[src:caching/hash-function] For example, text in any natural language has highly non-uniform distributions of characters, and character pairs, characteristic of the language.
[src:caching/hash-function] For such data, it is prudent to use a hash function that depends on all characters of the string—and depends on each character in a different way.
[src:caching/hash-function] Simplistic hash functions may add the first and last *n* characters of a string along with the length, or form a word-size hash from the middle 4 characters of a string.
[src:caching/hash-function] This saves iterating over the (potentially long) string, but hash functions that do not hash on all characters of a string can readily become linear due to redundancies, clustering, or other pathologies in the key set.
[src:caching/hash-function] Such strategies may be effective as a custom hash function if the structure of the keys is such that either the middle, ends, or other fields are zero or some other invariant constant that does not differentiate the keys; then the invariant parts of the keys can be ignored.
[src:caching/hash-function] The paradigmatic example of folding by characters is to add up the integer values of all the characters in the string.
[src:caching/hash-function] A better idea is to multiply the hash total by a constant, typically a sizable prime number, before adding in the next character, ignoring overflow.
[src:caching/hash-function] Using exclusive-or instead of addition is also a plausible alternative.
[src:caching/hash-function] The final operation would be a modulo, mask, or other function to reduce the word value to an index the size of the table.
[src:caching/hash-function] The weakness of this procedure is that information may cluster in the upper or lower bits of the bytes; this clustering will remain in the hashed result and cause more collisions than a proper randomizing hash.
[src:caching/hash-function] ASCII byte codes, for example, have an upper bit of 0, and printable strings do not use the last byte code or most of the first 32 byte codes, so the information, which uses the remaining byte codes, is clustered in the remaining bits in an unobvious manner.
[src:caching/hash-function] The classic approach, dubbed the PJW hash based on the work of Peter J.
[src:caching/hash-function] Weinberger at Bell Labs in the 1970s, was originally designed for hashing identifiers into compiler symbol tables as given in the "Dragon Book".
[src:caching/hash-function] This hash function offsets the bytes 4 bits before adding them together.
[src:caching/hash-function] When the quantity wraps, the high 4 bits are shifted out and if non-zero, xored back into the low byte of the cumulative quantity.
[src:caching/hash-function] The result is a word-size hash code to which a modulo or other reducing operation can be applied to produce the final hash index.
[src:caching/hash-function] Today, especially with the advent of 64-bit word sizes, much more efficient variable-length string hashing by word chunks is available.
[src:caching/hash-function] The final word, which may have unoccupied byte positions, is filled with zeros or a specified randomizing value before being folded into the hash.
[src:caching/hash-function] The accumulated hash code is reduced by a final modulo or other operation to yield an index into the table.
[src:caching/hash-function] Analogous to the way an ASCII or EBCDIC character string representing a decimal number is converted to a numeric quantity for computing, a variable-length string can be converted as *x**k*−1a*k*−1 + *x**k*−2a*k*−2 + ⋯ + *x*1*a* + *x*0.
[src:caching/hash-function] This is simply a polynomial in a radix *a* > 1 that takes the components (*x*0,*x*1,...,*x**k*−1) as the characters of the input string of length *k*.
[src:caching/hash-function] It can be used directly as the hash code, or a hash function applied to it to map the potentially large value to the hash table size.
[src:caching/hash-function] The value of *a* is usually a prime number large enough to hold the number of different characters in the character set of potential keys.
[src:caching/hash-function] Radix conversion hashing of strings minimizes the number of collisions.
[src:caching/hash-function] Available data sizes may restrict the maximum length of string that can be hashed with this method.
[src:caching/hash-function] For example, a 128-bit word will hash only a 26-character alphabetic string (ignoring case) with a radix of 29; a printable ASCII string is limited to 9 characters using radix 97 and a 64-bit word.
[src:caching/hash-function] However, alphabetic keys are usually of modest length, because keys must be stored in the hash table.
[src:caching/hash-function] Numeric character strings are usually not a problem; 64 bits can count up to 1019, or 19 decimal digits with radix 10.
[src:caching/hash-function] In some applications, such as substring search, one can compute a hash function *h* for every *k*-character substring of a given *n*-character string by advancing a window of width *k* characters along the string, where *k* is a fixed integer, and *n* > *k*.
[src:caching/hash-function] The straightforward solution, which is to extract such a substring at every character position in the text and compute *h* separately, requires a number of operations proportional to *k*·*n*.
[src:caching/hash-function] However, with the proper choice of *h*, one can use the technique of rolling hash to compute all those hashes with an effort proportional to *mk* + *n* where *m* is the number of occurrences of the substring.
[src:caching/hash-function] The hash function used for the algorithm is usually the Rabin fingerprint, designed to avoid collisions in 8-bit character strings, but other suitable hash functions are also used.
[src:caching/hash-function] Fuzzy hashing, also known as similarity hashing, is a technique for detecting data that is similar, but not exactly the same, as other data.
[src:caching/hash-function] This is in contrast to cryptographic hash functions, which are designed to have significantly different hashes for even minor differences.
[src:caching/hash-function] Fuzzy hashing has been used to identify malware and has potential for other applications, like data loss prevention and detecting multiple versions of code.
[src:caching/hash-function] Perceptual hashing is the use of a fingerprinting algorithm that produces a snippet, hash, or fingerprint of various forms of multimedia.
[src:caching/hash-function] A perceptual hash is a type of locality-sensitive hash, which is analogous if features of the multimedia are similar.
[src:caching/hash-function] This is in contrast to cryptographic hashing, which relies on the avalanche effect of a small change in input value creating a drastic change in output value.
[src:caching/hash-function] Perceptual hash functions are widely used in finding cases of online copyright infringement as well as in digital forensics because of the ability to have a correlation between hashes so similar data can be found (for instance with a differing watermark).
[src:caching/hash-function] Worst case results for a hash function can be assessed two ways: theoretical and practical.
[src:caching/hash-function] The theoretical worst case is the probability that all keys map to a single slot.
[src:caching/hash-function] The practical worst case is the expected longest probe sequence (hash function + collision resolution method).
[src:caching/hash-function] This analysis considers uniform hashing, that is, any key will map to any particular slot with probability 1/*m*, a characteristic of universal hash functions.
[src:caching/hash-function] While Knuth worries about adversarial attack on real time systems, Gonnet has shown that the probability of such a case is "ridiculously small".
[src:caching/hash-function] His representation was that the probability of *k* of *n* keys mapping to a single slot is α*k* / (*e*α *k*!), where *α* is the load factor, *n*/*m*.
[src:caching/hash-function] The term *hash* offers a natural analogy with its non-technical meaning (to chop up or make a mess out of something), given how hash functions scramble their input data to derive their output.
[src:caching/memcached] In computing **Memcached** (pronounced either /mɛmkæʃˈdiː/ *mem-cash-DEE* ["dee/d" being for daemon], or /ˈmɛmkæʃt/ *MEM-cashed*) is a general-purpose distributed memory-caching system.
[src:caching/memcached] It is often used to speed up dynamic database-driven websites by caching data and objects in RAM to reduce the number of times an external data source (such as a database or API) must be read.
[src:caching/memcached] Memcached is free and open-source software, licensed under the Revised BSD license.
[src:caching/memcached] Memcached runs on Unix-like operating systems (Linux and macOS) and on Microsoft Windows.
[src:caching/memcached] Memcached's APIs provide a large hash table distributed across multiple machines.
[src:caching/memcached] When the table is full, subsequent inserts cause older data to be purged in least recently used (LRU) order.
[src:caching/memcached] Applications using Memcached typically layer requests and additions into RAM before falling back on a slower backing store, such as a database.
[src:caching/memcached] Memcached has no internal mechanism to track misses which may happen.
[src:caching/memcached] However, some third party utilities provide this functionality.
[src:caching/memcached] Memcached was first developed by Brad Fitzpatrick for his website LiveJournal, on May 22, 2003.
[src:caching/memcached] It was originally written in Perl, then later rewritten in C by Anatoly Vorobey, who was employed by LiveJournal at the time.
[src:caching/memcached] Memcached is now used by many other systems, including YouTube, Reddit, Facebook, Pinterest, Twitter, Wikipedia, and Method Studios.
[src:caching/memcached] Google App Engine, Google Cloud Platform, Microsoft Azure, IBM Bluemix and Amazon Web Services also offer a Memcached service through an API.
[src:caching/memcached] The system uses a client–server architecture.
[src:caching/memcached] The servers maintain a key–value associative array; the clients populate this array and query it by key.
[src:caching/memcached] Keys are up to 250 bytes long and values can be at most 1 megabyte in size.
[src:caching/memcached] Clients use client-side libraries to contact the servers which, by default, expose their service at port 11211.
[src:caching/memcached] Each client knows all servers; the servers do not communicate with each other.
[src:caching/memcached] If a client wishes to set or read the value corresponding to a certain key, the client's library first computes a hash of the key to determine which server to use.
[src:caching/memcached] This gives a simple form of sharding and scalable shared-nothing architecture across the servers.
[src:caching/memcached] The server computes a second hash of the key to determine where to store or read the corresponding value.
[src:caching/memcached] The servers keep the values in RAM (and, starting in 1.6.0, in auxiliary cache on disk using an external storage server option); if a server runs out of available memory or disk, it discards the oldest values.
[src:caching/memcached] Therefore, clients must treat Memcached as a transitory cache; they cannot assume that data stored in Memcached is still there when they need it.
[src:caching/memcached] Other databases, such as MemcacheDB, Couchbase Server, provide persistent storage while maintaining Memcached protocol compatibility.
[src:caching/memcached] If all client libraries use the same hashing algorithm to determine servers, then clients can read each other's cached data.
[src:caching/memcached] A typical deployment has several servers and many clients.
[src:caching/memcached] However, it is possible to use Memcached on a single computer, acting simultaneously as client and server.
[src:caching/memcached] The size of its hash table is often very large.
[src:caching/memcached] It is limited to available memory across all the servers in the cluster of servers in a data center.
[src:caching/memcached] Where high-volume, wide-audience Web publishing requires it, this may stretch to many gigabytes.
[src:caching/memcached] Memcached can be equally valuable for situations where either the number of requests for content is high, or the cost of generating a particular piece of content is high.
[src:caching/memcached] Applications with particularly high-demand caching needs can use a built-in proxy to define and configure complex client-server routes.
[src:caching/memcached] Most deployments of Memcached are within trusted networks where clients may freely connect to any server.
[src:caching/memcached] However, sometimes Memcached is deployed in untrusted networks or where administrators want to exercise control over the clients that are connecting.
[src:caching/memcached] For this purpose Memcached can be compiled with optional SASL authentication support.
[src:caching/memcached] The SASL support requires the binary protocol.
[src:caching/memcached] A presentation at BlackHat USA 2010 revealed that a number of large public websites had left Memcached open to inspection, analysis, retrieval, and modification of data.
[src:caching/memcached] Even within a trusted organisation, the flat trust model of memcached may have security implications.
[src:caching/memcached] For efficient simplicity, all Memcached operations are treated equally.
[src:caching/memcached] Clients with a valid need for access to low-security entries within the cache gain access to *all* entries within the cache, even when these are higher-security and that client has no justifiable need for them.
[src:caching/memcached] If the cache key can be either predicted, guessed or found by exhaustive searching, its cache entry may be retrieved.
[src:caching/memcached] Some attempt to isolate setting and reading data may be made in situations such as high volume web publishing.
[src:caching/memcached] A farm of outward-facing content servers have *read* access to memcached containing published pages or page components, but no write access.
[src:caching/memcached] Where new content is published (and is not yet in memcached), a request is instead sent to content generation servers that are not publicly accessible to create the content unit and add it to memcached.
[src:caching/memcached] The content server then retries to retrieve it and serve it outwards.
[src:caching/memcached] In February 2018, CloudFlare reported that misconfigured memcached servers were used to launch DDoS attacks in large scale.
[src:caching/memcached] The memcached protocol over UDP has a huge amplification factor, of more than 51000.
[src:caching/memcached] Victims of the DDoS attacks include GitHub, which was flooded with 1.35 Tbit/s peak incoming traffic.
[src:caching/memcached] This issue was mitigated in Memcached version 1.5.6, which disabled UDP protocol by default.
[src:caching/memcached] Converting database or object creation queries to use Memcached is simple.
[src:caching/memcached] The client would first check whether a Memcached value with the unique key "userrow:userid" exists, where userid is some number.
[src:caching/memcached] If the result does not exist, it would select from the database as usual, and set the unique key using the Memcached API add function call.
[src:caching/memcached] However, if only this API call were modified, the server would end up fetching incorrect data following any database update actions: the Memcached "view" of the data would become out of date.
[src:caching/memcached] Therefore, in addition to creating an "add" call, an update call would also be needed using the Memcached set function.
[src:caching/memcached] This call would update the currently cached data to match the new data in the database, assuming the database query succeeds.
[src:caching/memcached] An alternative approach would be to invalidate the cache with the Memcached delete function, so that subsequent fetches result in a cache miss.
[src:caching/memcached] Similar action would need to be taken when database records were deleted, to maintain either a correct or incomplete cache.
[src:caching/memcached] An alternate cache-invalidation strategy is to store a random number in an agreed-upon cache entry and to incorporate this number into all keys that are used to store a particular kind of entry.
[src:caching/memcached] To invalidate all such entries at once, change the random number.
[src:caching/memcached] Existing entries (which were stored using the old number) will no longer be referenced and so will eventually expire or be recycled.
[src:caching/time-to-live] Under the Internet Protocol, TTL is an 8-bit field.
[src:caching/time-to-live] In the IPv4 header, TTL is the 9th octet of 20.
[src:caching/time-to-live] In the IPv6 header, it is the 8th octet of 40.
[src:caching/time-to-live] The maximum TTL value is 255, the maximum value of a single octet.
[src:caching/time-to-live] The time-to-live value can be thought of as an upper bound on the time that an IP datagram can exist in an Internet system.
[src:caching/time-to-live] The TTL field is set by the sender of the datagram, and reduced by every router on the route to its destination.
[src:caching/time-to-live] If the TTL field reaches zero before the datagram arrives at its destination, then the datagram is discarded and an Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) error datagram (11 - Time Exceeded) is sent back to the sender.
[src:caching/time-to-live] The purpose of the TTL field is to avoid a situation in which an undeliverable datagram keeps circulating on an Internet system, and such a system eventually becoming swamped by such "immortals".
[src:caching/time-to-live] In theory, under IPv4, time to live is measured in seconds, although every host that passes the datagram must reduce the TTL by at least one unit.
[src:caching/time-to-live] In practice, the TTL field is reduced by one on every hop.
[src:caching/time-to-live] To reflect this practice, the field is renamed *hop limit* in IPv6.
[src:caching/time-to-live] TTLs also occur in the Domain Name System (DNS), where they are set by an authoritative name server for a particular resource record.
[src:caching/time-to-live] When a caching (recursive) nameserver queries the authoritative nameserver for a resource record, it will cache that record for the time (in seconds) specified by the TTL.
[src:caching/time-to-live] If a stub resolver queries the caching nameserver for the same record before the TTL has expired, the caching server will simply reply with the already cached resource record rather than retrieve it from the authoritative nameserver again.
[src:caching/time-to-live] TTL for NXDOMAIN (non-existent domain) responses is set from the minimum of the MINIMUM field of the SOA record and the TTL of the SOA itself, and indicates how long a resolver may cache the negative answer.
[src:caching/time-to-live] Shorter TTLs can cause heavier loads on an authoritative name server, but can be useful when changing the address of critical services like web servers or MX records, and therefore are often lowered by the DNS administrator prior to a service being moved, in order to reduce possible disruptions.
[src:caching/time-to-live] An older common TTL value for DNS was 86400 seconds, which is 24 hours.
[src:caching/time-to-live] A TTL value of 86400 would mean that, if a DNS record was changed on the authoritative nameserver, DNS servers around the world could still be showing the old value from their cache for up to 24 hours after the last update by client.
[src:caching/time-to-live] Newer DNS methods that are part of a disaster recovery (DR) system may have some records deliberately set extremely low on TTL.
[src:caching/time-to-live] For example, a 300-second TTL would help key records expire in 5 minutes to help ensure these records are flushed quickly worldwide.
[src:caching/time-to-live] This gives administrators the ability to edit and update records in a timely manner.
[src:caching/time-to-live] TTL values are "per record" and setting this value on specific records is sometimes honored automatically by all standard DNS systems worldwide.
[src:caching/time-to-live] However, a problem persists in that some caching DNS nameservers set their own TTLs regardless of the authoritative records, thus it cannot be guaranteed that all downstream DNS servers have the new records after the TTL has expired.
[src:caching/time-to-live] Time to live may also be expressed as the date and time on which a record expires.
[src:caching/time-to-live] The `Expires:` header in HTTP responses, the `Cache-Control: max-age` header field in both requests and responses and the `expires` field in HTTP cookies express time-to-live in this way.
